Ensure that succeeding fund releases to NGOs/POs strictly adhere to the rules and regulations embodied in COA Circular Nos. 2007-001 and 2012-001.

We recommended and the Management agreed to the following courses of actions:
For the unreconciled discrepancies in the PPE accounts between the FS and supporting schedules, the Municipal Accountant to: (a) conduct an investigation to determine the cause and nature of the discrepancies; (b) gather all available PPE records from the accountable officers and the GSO to establish the accuracy of the reported PPE balances; and (c) implement the maintenance of SL, regularly update and reconcile the same with the GL balances;
For the existence of negative/abnormal balance, the Municipal Accountant to; (a) undertake a detailed reconciliation/analysis of the PPE and accumulated depreciation accounts; and (b) book up the necessary adjustments to derecognize the related accumulated depreciation and accumulated impairment losses, if any for those reclassified PPE items with cost below the capitalization threshold of ₱50,000.00 to eliminate negative/abnormal balance and arrive at the correct balances of the PPE accounts;
For the unrecorded donated PPEs, the Local Chief Executive (LCE) organize an Appraisal Committee tasked to come up with reasonable valuation/appraisal of PPE items found at station and those acquired through donation, which shall be the basis of the Municipal Accountant to recognize in the books of the Municipality in accordance with the guidelines set forth in IPSAS 17; and
PPE Ledger Cards, Real Property Ledger Cards and Property Cards for each group of PPEs shall be maintained by the Municipal Accountant and Municipal General Services Officer, respectively which shall be reconciled regularly pursuant to NGAS Manual for LGUs, Volume II.

We recommended and the Management agreed to the following:
At the beginning of the year, the Municipal Treasurer furnish the Municipal Accountant of a duly certified list showing the name of taxpayers and the amount due and collectible for the year;
The Municipal Accountant use the Real Property Tax Account Register/Taxpayer’s index card, Certified List of Taxpayers and Tax due and demandable submitted by the Municipal Treasurer as basis for setting up the RPT/SET receivables and deferred credits at the start of the year;
The Municipal Accountant maintain subsidiary ledgers for RPT/SET Receivables and Deferred Credits to facilitate easy reconciliation and monitoring of the balances; and
The Municipal Treasurer and the Municipal Accountant conduct reconciliation of records to establish a realistic balance of RPT and SET Receivables. Appropriate adjustments shall be made in the books for any discrepancies found thereto.

We recommended and the Management agreed to direct the Municipal Accountant to:
Analyze all the Receivables that are dormant, long outstanding and unsubstantiated for proper disposition and recognition;
Maintain subsidiary ledgers and supporting documents to substantiate the recorded balance of Receivable accounts;
Send demand letters to accountable officers, other Local Government Units (LGUs) and Non-Government Organizations (NGOs)/People’s Organization (POs) who are recipients of various fund releases from the Municipality to immediately liquidate or settle the funds received. Otherwise, cause the refund/payment of the outstanding balances due them; and
Exhaust all possible remedies to recover records/documents available to validate claims or else file a request for authority for the one-time cleansing of dormant accounts to the COA Audit Team Leader following the guidelines and procedures provided in COA Circular No. 2023-008 dated August 17, 2023.

We recommended and the Management agreed to require the:
Inventory Committee to conduct the physical count of all supplies and materials and prepare the RPCI, reconcile the results of the count with the SLC of the Accounting and stock cards of the GSO, and submit the RPCI to the Auditor pursuant to Section 124 of the MNGAS for LGUs, Volume I;
Designated GSO to ensure that purchases and issuance of supplies and materials are supported with duly signed RIS to establish accountability on the part of the end-users together with the SSMI which should be submitted to the Municipal Accountant;
Municipal Accountant upon submission of the required RIS and SSMI by the Designated GSO, compute for the costs of supplies issued and ending inventory using the moving average method, and recognize the appropriate expense account in compliance with Section 121 of the MNGAS for LGUs; and
The Municipal Accountant and the Designate GSO maintain the prescribed ledger cards and stock cards, respectively, for each type of Inventory, keep track of the actual Supplies Inventory on hand and reconcile the balances of the two inventory records;

We recommended and the Management agreed to direct the:
BAC to use the prescribed format of the Annual Procurement Plan and ensure that vital information is provided thereto in accordance with (GBBP) Resolution No. 20-2015 dated July 16, 2015;
Offices concerned to properly plan their procurement activities through the preparation of the Project Procurement Management Plan (PPMP) which contains all the anticipated materials, services, goods, civil works requirements and the BAC Secretariat to consolidate the same into an Annual Procurement Plan;
BAC to undertake procurement in bulk to save time, costs and manpower hours using public bidding as the primary mode of procurement and discontinue the practice of procuring supplies and equipment through shopping or small value procurement unless the conditions in Section 52.1 and 53.9 of the Revised IRR of RA 9184 are met; and
BAC, TWG and Secretariat to avoid/stop splitting of contracts in compliance with the revised IRR of RA No. 9184.

We recommended and the Management agreed to the following:
Limit the practice of serving meals and snacks during meetings particularly those events which are considered among the regular functions or normal activities of the Municipality. Instead, focus the utilization of the government funds for purposes which are more beneficial to the constituents;
Observe economy and austerity measures in the use of government funds which are intended for public purpose;
The Municipal Budget Officer properly charge or limit such expenditures against appropriations for Representation Expenses, Extraordinary and Miscellaneous Expenses, or Discretionary Fund, which are provided for the purpose; and
The Municipal Accountant ensure the completeness of required documents to support the propriety of payments.

We recommended and the Management agreed to direct the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer to:
Review their respective records (GL and Cashbook) to account for the difference of ₱1.713 million by comparing each other’s entries in their respective records;
Effect the necessary adjustments in their respective records to come up with the accurate Cash-Local Treasury and Cash in Bank account balances;
Henceforth, conduct thorough periodic reconciliation between their respective records so that errors in recording will be corrected/adjusted at the earliest possible time; and
Adhere with the periodic submission of bank reconciliation statements, cashbooks and other financial reports to the Office of the Auditor for review and validation of cash balances, so that errors or deficiencies that may be found in audit could be promptly communicated to the concerned personnel.

We recommended and Management agreed to the following:
LDRRMO and Municipal Budget Officer to allocate not less than five percent of the estimated revenue from regular sources for LDRRMF to support disaster risk management activities;
Local Chief Executive to instruct the assigned LDRRMO, Municipal Planning and Development Coordinator (MPDC) and Local DRRM Council to prepare and furnish the Audit Team with a comprehensive and integrated LDRRMIP that includes not only current appropriation but also those PPAs under the continuing appropriations and the list of projects and activities charged to the unexpended LDRRMF under the Special Trust Fund, as required under Republic Act (RA) No. 10121, and Sections 5.1.2 and 5.1.15 of COA Circular No. 2012-002 dated September 12, 2002;
Municipal Accountant prepare the required monthly Report on Sources and Utilization of LDRRM Fund and the same shall be submitted to this Office by the LDRRMO on or before the 15th day after the end of each month; and
Management take full advantage of the LDRRM fund through optimal utilization of the funds provided for programs and projects designed and intended to build a disaster-resilient community.

