The LDRRMC ensure that the proposed PPAs chargeable against the LDRRMF are strictly related for disaster prevention and mitigation, preparedness, response and rehabilitation and recovery; 

Management ensure optimum utilization of the calamity fund for expenditures that address the key objectives of disaster risk reduction and management as envisioned under R.A. No. 10121; and

The Municipal Accountant to: (a) conduct an investigation and reconciliation on the noted discrepancy amounting to ₱3.358 million; and (b) record the necessary adjusting entry to correct the amount of Trust Liability-DRRM account.

The GSO prepare the required RIS and RSMI for all issued relief goods, supplies and materials which should be submitted to the Accounting Unit for the recording of appropriate expense;

The requisitioning department prepare and submit: (i) the list of beneficiaries indicating the quantity and specifics of items distributed and the signature of recipients signifying their acceptance/acknowledgement of the relief/welfare goods; and (ii) photographs taken during distribution of said items to the beneficiaries; and

The Municipal Accountant: (i) record the expense only upon receipt of RIS and RSMI from the GSO and other supporting documents; and (ii) ensure that the release and use of the QRF be supported with Local Sanggunian Resolution.

Management require the contractor to fast track the completion of the projects to avoid possible rescindment of contracts as stipulated in Section 68 of RA No. 9184;

The Municipal Engineer intensify the monitoring activities through routine inspections of infrastructure development projects from the commencement of implementation, during construction and upon completion thereof in order to avoid recurrence of delayed project delivery to the intended beneficiaries;

The Municipal Accountant compute and impose liquidated damages at least equal to one-tenth of one percent (0.001) of the cost of the unperformed portion for every day of delay which shall be withheld upon final payment without prejudice to other appropriate sanctions that will be imposed by the Management to the erring contractor; and

The Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) carefully evaluate the prospective bidder’s technical, legal and financial capabilities taking into consideration the history and experience of the Municipality with the contractor relative to project undertakings, so that contracts for infrastructure development projects are awarded only to contractors that are reliable to accomplish the projects on time.

