We recommended that:

The Sangguniang Bayan during the preparation of the Annual Budget for 20% Development Fund include only Programs/Projects/Activities which are feasible and could be accomplished within the target date of completion, after taking into consideration the priorities of the LGU leadership;

Implement the development projects programmed during the year as embodied in the Annual Investment/Development Plan and ensure optimum utilization of the 20% Development Fund in compliance with the provisions of DILG and DBM Joint Memorandum Circular No. 2017-1 dated February 22, 2017 for the benefit of the constituents of the Municipality;

Implement immediately all the projects under the continuing appropriations; and

At the end of each year, review all unimplemented projects and verify whether they can be implemented in the succeeding year. All savings from completed projects and all projects which are no longer feasible and cannot be implemented should be considered for immediate realignment, subject to budgetary rules or reverted back to the unappropriated surplus of the 20% Development Fund for re-appropriation to other development projects.

We recommended that:
The Municipal Mayor instruct the General Services Officer Designate to prepare the corresponding Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Property (IIRUP) for the identified unserviceable properties and initiate the process of disposing the unserviceable properties in accordance with Section 79 of PD 1445 and in accordance with the provisions cited in COA Circular No. 89-296;
Management instruct the General Services Officer Designate to give priority in identifying the accountable persons for the missing/lost properties and require them to settle their accountabilities and/or submit request for relief of accountability in accordance with Section 73 of PD 1445;
Management create a Disposal and Appraisal Committee which will prepare the appraisal Report on the value of unserviceable properties and undertake the necessary action/s for the immediate disposal of the unserviceable properties to avoid further deterioration and consequent depreciation in value; and
After the disposal, require the General Services Officer to submit the necessary documents, together with the Official Receipt to the Accounting Office as the basis of the latter to drop the unserviceable properties from the book of accounts in accordance with the existing accounting and auditing rules and regulations.

We recommended that:
The Municipal Assessor furnish the Municipal Treasurer on or before the 31st day of December of each year, an assessment roll containing a list of  all real property, whether taxable or exempt, located within the territorial jurisdiction of the Municipal Government of Numancia, Aklan and a list of all persons whose real properties have been newly assessed or reassessed and the values of such properties;
The Municipal Treasurer prepare a duly certified list showing the name of the taxpayers and the amount due and collectible for the year and submit the same to the Municipal Accountant to serve as the basis in setting up the beginning balance of RPT/SET Receivable in the books of accounts. In such manner, the related receivable account and deferred liability will be presented fairly in the financial statements;
The Municipal Treasurer and the Municipal Accountant conduct reconciliation of records to establish a realistic balance of receivables for the RPT Taxes and SET Taxes so that necessary adjustment(s) in the books of accounts can be effected for a more realistic presentation of the balances in the financial statements;
The Municipal Treasurer religiously update the individual Real Property Tax Account Register (RPTAR) or Taxpayer’s Index Card every time a payment is received from the taxpayer which shall serve as the basis in the preparation of the List of Delinquent Real Property Taxpayers as of the end of the year, the total of which shall equal the RPT/SET Receivable at year end; and
The Local Chief Executive (LCE), Municipal Treasurer and other concerned Municipal Officials exert concerted efforts to intensify collections of long outstanding RPT and SET Receivables including the interest thereon so that more development programs may be implemented for the benefit of the constituents.

We recommended that:
The Sangguniang Bayan during the preparation of the Annual Budget for 20% Development Fund include only Programs/Projects/Activities which are feasible and could be accomplished within the target date of completion, after taking into consideration the priorities of the LGU leadership;
Implement the development projects programmed during the year as embodied in the Annual Investment/Development Plan and ensure optimum utilization of the 20% Development Fund in compliance with the provisions of DILG and DBM Joint Memorandum Circular No. 2017-1 dated February 22, 2017 for the benefit of the constituents of the Municipality;
Implement immediately all the projects under the continuing appropriations; and
At the end of each year, review all unimplemented projects and verify whether they can be implemented in the succeeding year. All savings from completed projects and all projects which are no longer feasible and cannot be implemented should be considered for immediate realignment, subject to budgetary rules or reverted back to the unappropriated surplus of the 20% Development Fund for re-appropriation to other development projects.

We recommended that Management:
Desist from charging to government funds the expenses in connection with the Search for Miss Numancia 2019, Oath Taking Ceremony of newly-elected officials, Sangguniang Kabataan (SK) Night, DepEd Night, Grand Binayle, Musikadya 2019, Kite Festival and other events prohibited under Section 335 and 342 of R.A. No. 7160;
Limit the expenses for catering services and observe prudence in utilizing government funds which are intended for public purpose;
Record the expenses incurred to the appropriate account title category as provided in the Revised Chart of Accounts for LGUs under the Philippine Public Sector Accounting Standards (PPSAS);
Limit the use of “Other Maintenance and Operating Expenses” (05-02-99-990) account for expenses not otherwise classified under the specific maintenance and  other  operating  expenses  accounts  and record  appropriate  expense  accounts  based   on   the   accurate classification  of  financial  transactions   as   documented   and supported by the accounting records pursuant to Annex B, Section 5.2 of COA Circular No. 2015-009 dated December 1, 2015; and
Expenses for meals and snacks incurred during meetings and conferences of officials/department heads  in  the  performance  of  their  regular duties/functions shall be charged to their respective Representation Allowance (RA).

We recommended that Management:
Direct the Municipal Accountant to exert extra effort to work back and review entries to account for the discrepancies noted and make necessary adjusting entries to correct the balances of affected accounts and remit any unremitted amount, if there is any;
Require the Municipal Treasurer to timely submit liquidation reports on the payment of salaries and wages so that the accounting department can immediately record the same in order to avoid the late recognition of mandatory premium contributions and payment of loan amortizations;
Direct the staff tasked to prepare the remittances to reconcile the same with the amount collected before the disbursement voucher for the payment to concerned agencies are prepared and ensure that mandatory premium contributions and loan payments collected from employees are remitted promptly and in full amount to the concerned agencies; and
Make representations with the concerned officials of the GSIS, Pag-IBIG and PhilHealth as regards the settlement of the prior year’s unremitted contributions/payments to avoid the imposition of interests, surcharges and penalties.

Recommendation:
We recommended that Management
Require the Municipal Accountant to compute the correct depreciation expenses of its assets and a journal entry must be drawn to update/correct the accumulated depreciation by a debit to depreciation expense (for the current year depreciation), debit to prior year’s adjustment (for the prior year’s depreciation) and a credit to accumulated depreciation (for the total unrecorded depreciation);
Exert effort through the General Services Office, to reconstruct and update its property records and reconcile with the accounting records to facilitate the setting up and periodic provision of depreciation for those depreciable assets not provided with depreciation;
Create an appraisal committee to conduct evaluation of assets whose records could not be found in order to establish the commencement of depreciation of the subjected assets and determine their depreciable cost and estimated remaining life for the computation of their respective depreciation; and
Henceforth, the Municipal Accountant see to it that all depreciable properties owned by the LGU are provided with depreciation in accordance with the above-mentioned rules and regulations to ensure its fair presentation in the financial statements.

